FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE - SOUTH KOREA (11): (NORTH GYEOMGSANG), UPDATE
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Wed 1 Dec 2010
Source: USAgNet via Wisconsinagconnection.com [edited]
<http://www.wisconsinagconnection.com/story-national.php?Id=2394&yr=2010>


South Korea reported 3 more suspected cases of foot-and-mouth disease
[FMD] on Wed 1 Dec 2010, despite its strong efforts to curb the
spread of the animal disease.

The suspected cases were reported at cow farms in a southeastern city
where an outbreak was 1st reported Monday [29 Nov 2010]. The results
of tests on additional farms will be available Thursday [2 Dec 2010],
according to the Ministry of Food, Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries.

South Korea has taken strong measures to prevent the spread of the
animal disease that affects all cloven-hoofed animals, including
pigs, sheep and goats, since the outbreak was reported at 2 pig farms
in the southeastern city of Andong, about 270 km southeast of Seoul.

The price of domestic beef shot up 9.6 percent Tuesday [30 Nov 2010]
as the number of cattle slaughtered dropped from the daily average of
930 head in October 2010 to 273 head on Monday [29 Nov 2010], when
tests on the 2 pig farms confirmed an outbreak of the disease. The
disease or meat from infected animals does not affect humans.

An additional case was confirmed Tuesday [30 Nov 2010] at a cow farm,
also in Andong. The affected farms have some 9150 head of animals,
but an additional 24 000 animals at nearby farms will also be
destroyed to prevent a further spread, the ministry said.

--
Communicated by:
FMD News
FMD Surveillance and Modeling Laboratory
University of California at Davis, USA
<http://fmd.ucdavis.edu/news.php>
